description.text:
Here is my interpretation of the X-Wing Pilot Comm Pad for Star Wars: A New Hope.
This Comm Pad has been sized to fit RL quality costume flight suits with the windowed arm pocket. It has a wider base built specifically for keeping all of the important bits visible in the window. You may need to trim or add to this to get it to fit your particular flight suit.

I offer this in different options. You can print the One-Piece version in white and paint the buttons whatever color you like. Or you can print the parts individually in any color you want All you need to do is glue the pieces together.
You also have a choice of two styles of face plate. Both styles have curved backing for your arm, but one has a flat face and the other has a curved face. The curved face is more accurate but I thought the flat one looked cool too. So it's your choice.

It is recommended that you print it standing up. It'll be stronger and cleaner than if you print it laying on its back. Takes less support and won't give you map lines.

If you make one for your costume, please post pictures!!

MTFBWY!

title: DAN A4-SFX USB C Mod Clip

description.text:
This is a modification for the DAN A4-SFX computer case. It's used so that you can replace the USB 3.0 Type A connector with a USB 3.1 Gen 2 Type C connector. I used the Lian-Li PW-IC01NH45 cable (http://bit.ly/2fvjwCV). I had to modify the cable by cutting off the screw holes, as I've shown in one of the images.

Once you've unscrewed and removed the Type A connector, place the clip into the existing hole on the inside. Then, slide the Type C cable into the clip, until it reaches the outer panel (see images).

The cable fit snugly enough for me that I was able to plug things into it without the cable pushing back out. You could use hot glue or something to secure the cable into the clip if you desire.

While this could be printed vertically without support material, the clips could break off easily, as they'd be flexing in the same plane as the layers. I printed mine on it's side, so that the plane of motion was perpendicular to the plane of the layers, making it stronger.

description.text:
This is a spool holder of my own design intended to be screwed down onto a surface. In addition to the printed parts you will need the following:

688z bearings - 2 for each wheel - There are four wheels required to fit one spool so a total of 8 bearings required per spool mounted.
M8 Bolts - 2 per stand - suggested length 40mm. Smooth shaft for free running, Fully threaded for a little resistance.
M8 Nuts - 1 for each bolt you use ;)

When assembling make sure you don't tighten the bolts. There should be a little distance between the uprights and the wheel so that it can rotate freely.

The Files

I've provided a layout of parts sufficient to make a stand for one spool. Files for the individual parts can be downloaded separately if this proves more convenient. If downloading parts separately you would need 4 uprights, 4 mounts and 4 wheels to support one spool.

Optional

Screws to mount the stands to a surface. Type of screw will be dependant on what surface you're attaching.
Glue to fix the stands in place on the mounts. The friction fit should be fairly good but if you want to be sure they will not move glue them in place. Again choose an adhesive that suits the material you're printing.

title: Destiny Ghost - Fast print / Snap fit

description.text:
Modeled the Destiny Ghost to be quickly printable / put together, single shells save a lot of time and the output is cleaner, the main body just snaps together after printing.

V1.1:

  • Square pegs to connect the shells, much stronger / easier to print.
  • Scaled to reasonable dimensions, ( ~RL size of the ghost ) fits 150x150 print bed, final full dimensions unscaled are 135mm width 139mm height 105mm depth without stand.
  • Added the central sphere as Iges so it can be customized by you fine folks.

V1.2:

  • Fixed a minor mistake on the eye spheres

V1.3:

  • added a "bigger" eye cap

Stand 1.0:

  • Added a stand for the ghost.

LED Tealight 1.0:

  • Added a new back sphere and a corresponding knob to outfit the ghost with a led tealight.

https://www.ebay.com/itm/171239692713?_trksid=p2059210.m2749.l2649&var=470455566681&ssPageName=STRK%3AMEBIDX%3AIT
All parts beside the orange tips snap fit together, use superglue to glue the caps to the main body.

Main assembly

Use supports for the central part of the outside shell ( Steep spherical overhang )

Make sure you have adequate cooling for PLA ( atleast one 50mm blower straight to the nozzle ) and 45° overhangs print perfectly on your machine before attempting this print.

If the pegs are to tight print them at ~97% ( they do fit on a lin_adv + perfectly dialed in printer but you wont be able to take the ghost apart again ;) )

Use superglue to glue the LED tealight to the back half sphere and the knob. ( can still be unscrewed completely to change the led / battery )

Print the eye cap, blue glass and orange tips @ 0.1 layer height.

LED Back sphere

Print the knob with supports and @0.1 layer height

Stand

Print without supports, superglue logo.

Central spherical shells

Use supports for the central part of the shell ( Steep spherical overhang )

Use multiple processes to get the best results, 0.2 up to where the ring indents end, 0.1 for a smoother top surface.

title: Nerf Recon MKII Pump Action Kit

description.text:
This is a modified version of the pump action kit that was originally created by the user, jebleez. It the grip file was then modified by a different user, Scrutmonkey to be used with different arms for a Recon MK II. A third user then created cage arms that are more durable than the other arms. This is a complete kit for my Recon MK II pump action kit.

I modified the barrel to have a wider diameter barrel to reduce barrel drag. I also added an orange tip in order to make it follow any toy gun laws requiring them to have one. The grip and cage arms are unmodified by me.

My Recon is modified with an Orange Mod Works Stage 1 Retaliator kit. The parts do not yet show any signs of stress from the upgraded spring. I also did not install the two small screws that hold the slide to the shell. This allows me to take out the two screws in the arms and reinstall the stock slide without taking apart the entire blaster.

Update 12/3 - I modified the grip to attach to metal arms instead of the plastic ones. This makes priming more reliable. As the plastic arms started to wear out, it started making the blaster harder to prime. I used 10-24 screws and a 1/8x3/4 inch metal bar. A full build guide is coming soon.

title: Wooden Train Bridge Supports - Alphabet (6mm letters, 2 or 4mm joiner plate)

description.text:
This is a set of letter supports with a track joiner. With the letter and joiner the support is 64mm high under the track. This works with the current bridges I have purchase but you should check for bridge ramp height or supports. You can scale the letters to support a different height. Measure your current bridge support height
The letters are 60mm high and the joiner base plate is 2mm or 4mm. I based this height off a Thomas bridge I have which is 64mm but others have 62mm. A discrepancy of a couple millimeters should not be a problem.

I recommend no more than 10% infill.  These are still very string at that level.  
Print a joiner for each letter and join with epoxy or glue of choice.  Keep an eye on the direction of the letters as you glue the plate to them.
There is a 2mm and 4 mm joiner plate option for small discrepencies in your current bridge.

description.header: Still not quite right, then scale
description.text:
Don't scale the Joiner, just the letters if your bridge is a different height. You want to scale only by the X and Y axis. Leave scale of Z as 1, assuming you are printing these as the STL has them oriented with the letters facing up.
  • Measure your bridge height in mm
  • ((your_height - 4) * 1.6 = scale %
  • if you are using slic3r then this would be that percentage / 100. i.e. if the scale % was 93 then the slic3r scale is 0.93.

description.text:
Our artistic interpretation(sketch) of Peter Quill's Spaceship from Guardians of the Galaxy by Marvell Studio's(ALL RIGHTS RESERVED).
This is the low-poly version(19.5MB), due to the filesize of the high-res(181MB).

comments.text:
just printed it on a 200x200mm bed. in repetier, set each part's stl scale to 0.3, or lower if your Z aint that high.
i printed gcode for a 0.4mmnozzle on a 0.35mm nozzle printer, but it came out ok.
one wing (the pivoting one) touched the bed only half the first layer, but it stil fit.
the wing with the long pin had to loose most of the pin, and had to be glued in.
the bottom wing has way too much tolerance, and will need glueing for sure, that or a printing pen.
i printed:
one bed for the left fuselage
one bed for the mirror right fuselage
and one bed for all the little things, and their mirrors.
It does need sufficient print cooling.
and a little cutterknife to account for the shrunken tolerances.
All and all, it feels like building plastic model kits. It looks awesome assembled, but needs some glue and paint.

Printing and assembly tips

Printing tips
1-As with most of my models, no supports are required.

2-Be sure to clean any first layer squish if you have any problem joining parts. The parts should fit nicely when printed cleanly or with a slight first layer squish.

3-I did not require any rafts or brims for any of the parts, however use your judgement as some parts have small bases:
hand_left
hand_right
arm_left
arm_right

..
Assembly tips:
1-The left/right eyebrows are quite small and are actually modeled to fit a certain way, however since they are so small that as long as they look good it should be fine any way they are positioned.

2-The left/right eyewhites and left/right eyeblacks are interchangeable.

3-Before gluing the stripes and buckle, be sure to bend them a bit since they are being glued to a slightly rounded part.

4-If the rings around the pants are too snug, simply sand a tiny bit off the part that touches the pants. A tiny sanding makes a big difference in how high the rings fit.

5-Since there are a bunch of tiny black parts I printed two sets of each part. I knew I'd drop and lose a part while putting the model together.

6-Refer to the assembly diagram for putting the model together. The model is meant to be glued.

description.text:
I had some issues from the very beginning with the z motor mount. The first time i put my machine together i cracked the part where the bolts tighten up. I replaced it shortly after, but was very careful not to over tighten. Recently it actually came off of the tubes and my spindle free falled into the material. Not good…So i found an existing stronger motor mount on thingiverse and modified it. I extended the round portion down to just above the bearing plate below. Because this has a lot more bearing surface it also keeps the part more square when tightening down. Around the bolts this part is much beefier as well, and i could crank it down without cracking. This part also has the provisions to actually drill a through hole in your tubing and pass a long 6-32 bolt through all of it. There is a recessed portion for the head of the bolt and a flat for the nut on the opposing side. It turned out really great, hope someone else can use it.

I always wanted to have extruder style that can be changed without taking off everything. But on prusa mk2 series, the wires were fixed together at the back of the x-carriage.

This is a proof of concept but should be usable. Only that the wiring to the motor itself can't be together with the rest of the electronic behind the x-carriage if you want to change between bowden and direct drive.

Do help me test this and report back if it works, your feedback are appreciated =D

About the Models

There are 2 main parts for the sets above; extruder and hotend. The hotend part where it will house the hotend where the models name starts with "hotend..."

Other than that is the extruder style you want to pair with the hotend parts above. For example you uses bltouch sensor, use "direct 8mm BLTOUCH.stl". Because this naming schemes indicates that it is compatible with the 8mm inductive sensor/probe with the bltouch systems. the rest of them has different thickness as introduced in my previous prusa mk2 extruder sets

If you want to use bowden, use "bowden.stl" it is actually just a generic spacer so that when fitting the hotend to the x-carriage, there will be a good 90' angle

Compatibility

I found out that the original direct drive are not compatible with the most of the direct drive gears out there such as mk8 extruder or generic geared extruder. I searched the net that Prusa3d's extruder are 6mm in diameter while others are 7-11mm diameter. Info can be found here https://shop.prusa3d.com/forum/original-prusa-i3-mk2-f23/why-is-the-extruder-pulley-made-of-brass--t1105-s20.html#p20314

I am going to create a new direct extruder to cater these needs

It consists of three pieces that have to be glued together.  Two straps will be needed to secure the holster.  One  around a worn belt and the other around the leg.   I cut and used an old belt for my straps.  
The pieces, if placed properly on the build plate will not need supports and print in about 7 to 8 hours on the default low print quality.  I've also included an optional buckle that I used to secure the top strap.

author: masood17318

description.text:
As many Sega fans can probably attest, it's really annoying when you buy a game with a broken case that will not shut properly. This is usually caused by a little plastic latch breaking, especially on cases that used more brittle material. I designed this replacement latch in Autodesk Maya after carefully measuring the original from a Sega case I had with a broken latch, after a failed attempt at repairing it by more conventional means. This replacement design really works!

Print the clip using a fairly strong material like ABS, at your printer's highest resolution and going slow at 100% infill. I recommend printing up a batch of several in case you have any defects. Heat your bed to about 110C and have a fairly hot nozzle temperature (I used 240C with Hatchbox ABS) to ensure that you will have a strong bond between your layers. I've designed the latch in such a way that you don't need any support material.

Using a pair of flush cutters and an exacto knife, completely remove the remains of the original clip and scrape the surface smooth. You don't want anything getting in the way of the new latch clip when you install it.

Sand the bottom of the latch lightly to give glue a good clinging surface, then wipe down with alcohol. Do the same on the spots on the case where you will be attaching the clip. The tricky part will be lining up the clip correctly so that it is not too close or too far from the edge of the case, but if you have a case with at least one non-broken clip for reference you should be fine. Use a strong 2 part epoxy to attach the clip to the case. Give the epoxy about 24 hours to cure completely before attempting to close the case. Make sure you don't get any epoxy on the clear plastic sleeve!

Do all this correctly and your previously broken Sega case should work good as new!

description.text:
This add on fixes 3 issues with the stock feed head on a Monoprice Maker Select Ultimate or a Wanhao D6 (they are the same printer design).

1) Prevents the filament from wearing a grove in the hole the filament is fed into from the top of the printhead while it allows the filament to have a gentle turn from the spool.
I have added a picture where I use a piece of mechanics wire and hold it with screws in holes I drill in the side. The print does not have these holes yet but see picture with the wire.

2) Holds in the ribbon cable which causes endless grief as it creeps out after a lot of use.

3) Eases the turn that the ribbon cable has to make to get into it's connector on top

A version 1 remains on this post which does not address ribbon cable issues but does fix the filament hole problem #1 above.

Best print is when the part grows out of one side of it much like a real extrusion would grow so see the STL picture that shows a good orientation for the prints.

I noticed after making perhaps 50 prints that the hole on top of the printhead was being enlarged by friction from the filament and poor quality plastic perhaps. I also noticed that the filament fed from behind the machine and the ribbon cable was having to make a fairly tight bend to go down the feed hole. Lastly I had issues with the ribbon cable working it's way out of the connector after the hot glue they used had broken free.

This part is installed by removing the top 2 black screws that hold the printhead to the 1/16" metal plate. Then this part is placed as shown in my install picture and then the use of 2 M3 screws of 12mm length hold this print onto the location shown.

Because the filament will in time eat away at this part you simply make another one of these later and you have not destroyed a part of the printer that may be really hard to find.

description.text: I broke the display on my new e-bike when putting the bike in my van. Two little ridges that slide into the bike mount grooves broke off. I needed a polygon with many many square corners. Each point in the list only changes X or Y from the previous point so I made a list alternating X and Y jogs in a Perl script. title: Wobble Decouplers (beta) for Wanhao Duplicator i3, Monoprice Maker Select i3, Powerspec, Cocoon Create, Other Clones

description.text:
EDIT: 4/2/2018 Looking for 'commits' for how far to shorten the length as it doesn't require the entire distance to function. If anyone has a preference let me know, or multiple people so there's some discussion.

Sorry for typo, it's flange, not flanger. Subtleties, moving on.

Preparations:

-Phillips screw driver (try different ones out to see which isn't going to strip your screw. Don't force. The stock [flanges] T8 nut screws are pretty fine and they need a little bit of careful torque to get out. Again, careful- they will easily strip-you very much don't want that.)

-New [flanges] T8 nuts provided in the link at the bottom.

-Calipers (any). To level the z motors.

-Hex key set.

-Perhaps a second hand or someone that knows what they're doing.

Update Nov. 16 2017

This model I bought was refurbished poorly and the after pictures don't really reflect this item's potential. I've been getting even better prints than before but pictures wouldn't be accurate to its original configuration. This machine was listed as a refurb but it was more As-is than anything. I've never spent that much money getting something which is refurbished, to function in the first place. There are people that swear by refurb quality but I got the scud of the bunch so to speak.

Update Oct. 17 2017

I added pictures of before and after, although my printer's extruder is really inconsistent and I'm working on that detail while planning to switch to bowden. But in the pictures is b and a

WARNING: DO THIS AT YOUR OWN DISCRETION. IF YOU DAMAGE YOUR PRINTER IT IS YOUR OWN FAULT. I INSTALLED THIS JUST FINE. MAKE SURE TO USE A SIMILAR SCREW DRIVER TO THE PICTURE.

Update Oct. 11th 2017

I've added pictures on more less what it looks like being installed. You need to take the original [flanges] T8 nuts off and leave them off. Use the Amazon t8 nuts provided in the link. The stock t8 nuts are different and I can't guarantee it working at all. It's almost a requirement to have new ones because transplanting them during the process would be a pain in the rear.

Update Oct. 10th 2017

I uploaded Alpha v .6. The screw holes are adjusted and the forks are shorter. I'm printing this right now after a failed try when my octoprint was unplugged. I'll have pictures very soon. IMPORTANT: I did not need to move my limit switch. No extra step.

Was able to test the hole sizes with the failed print. Appropriate size.

WARNING:

  • You have to remove the original [flange] t8 nut from the gantry before you install this. There is a link to a proper nut below as the stock one was too difficult to find reference for. It's the same threaded flange and a little shorter so it's best to use that one, as I don't even know if the stock one works. This is why it's beta.

Use this to move your limit switch if needed:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1788330

Background:

This is a wobble decoupler which works on either side of the x axis to guide the threaded rods and reduce wobble and inconsistencies in prints. This was designed to be similar to the FLSUN i3 wobble decouplers, yet for the Wanhao Duplicator i3/ i3 plus, 2.1- Monoprice Maker Select, Maker Select Plus, and other clones of those printers.

Original idea:

https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1804112

One way of explaining it is, a train always feels every little bump on the tracks- an elevator kind of glides. One is on a set rail, the other is on a cable so to speak, in this case- the axel is disconnected so it doesn't feel every little inconsistency in the threaded rod. edit: the gantry rests on top of it, using gravity to lift up and down. Also if something bumps, it's a tiny bit like shock absorbance.

It requires a standard [flange] T8 nut which I'm not sure is the same size as the default because I couldn't find that exact one to use for reference. It is just a bit bigger but it may work. I figure it's probably easier in the installation as you don't have to transplant anything.

Here's a compatible nut:

Amazon [flanges] t8 mounting nuts
http://amzn.to/2wXMG8L

The one I tested and verified working got poor reviews for some reason. I don't know why considering mine work fine and give great prints. Due to that, here's another link for flanges from hictop, whom are suppliers of the Cr-10.

http://amzn.to/2CnqEdw

This is a work in progress. It is not meant to be used as a crutch for reliability as this is the beta test. While it seems I measured everything correctly, we're relying on human accuracy, 79 cent calipers, and mechanical reference.

To install:

Screw t8 nut to wobble decouplers opposite way to each one.

Remove top and slowly screw rods on x axis until it is removed from the top.

Remove stock t8 nut

Insert prepared decouplers on either side from top with t8 nut base hanging down.

Reinstall x axis by carefully sliding down. It shouldn't be connected to the threaded rod, just giving it clearance.

Reinstall top.

Level either threaded rod with calipers.

Test.

Please leave comments with your experiences.

The ascii was the first draft blue print, those may not reflect the actual dimensions.

Update: fixed screw hole size just after uploading. Now threads grip plastic better.

Printer and t8 nut You will need a Wanhao Duplicator i3, a MP Maker Select i3, or a clone of those types of printer. http://amzn.to/2xGfnUP http://amzn.to/2k8p5vZ http://amzn.to/2x1I0yQ https://www.aldi.co.uk/3d-printer You will need flanges/t8 nuts as well. http://amzn.to/2ycmjMG

title: Duckietown Duckiebot Battery Holder for Asus Powerbank

description.text:
This is a battery holder for the Duckiebot described in: http://duckietown.org.

For the robot, we want to pack in a big power-bank that powers the raspberry pi. But securing the battery with tape or Velcro is sometimes problematic.

So we made this part, that has holes and fasteners precisely located as the dagu magician chassis. Also we tried to put the battery as low as possible, and distribute it weight to that it has a nice center of weight.

We are including the sketch-up file, so you can modify it for maybe another kind of power bank.

Notice to use this part, you will also need to use the motor mount, which ties the motors to the chassis, but without using the red little parts included in the dagu chassis.

After printing pop in M3 nuts by pushing them with the back of a screwdriver. The mount the piece on the chassis by using plastic M3 screws. I cut straps from 2mm thick cork material, and laid them inside the mount, then put the battery in, charging ports facing rear or the robot. Then I glued a piece of foamy material on top of the battery, so it will securely be in place when the chassis is mounted from the top, but yet be still removable this way.

This is a motor mount for robots described in: http://duckietown.org

The purpose of this part, is to mount the plastic motors to the DAGU chassis. The original motor mounting method is by means of using 4 red little plastic pieces that hang from the top and the motors are squeezed with screws. We observed this caused problems:

a. after wheel calibration is done, and the robot is used for a while, the calibrations will change, because the motor mount will move.

b. by using screws to mount the motors from the side, it squeezes the gearbox. this causes the initial power that is required the motor to move vary. It will require a lot of current just to move first, then require less current. So, if you squeeze those screws too much, it will cause the robot to make a S pattern, caused by algorithm trying to correct the motors.

c. the red little parts protrude the chassis, obstructing battery mounting.

So we designed this part. This is a work in progress, and we have not really achieved to solve a.

After printing pop in 5 plastic M3 nuts to the bottom of the part that will mount the piece to the chassis. Use 4 M3 metal nuts for the motor mount holes. Notice that M3 metal nuts are slightly smaller. Pop them in, and glue them. I used few drops of ABS cement. The photos with the white parts show how the screws should be put in place,

Mount it to the chassis, it will guide the motors nicely. Then attach the 2 little parts to the sides, and screw them in - the plates should just touch the motors, do not squeeze the screws too much. The last three photos illustrate how the piece is mounted.

This part serves as an axle, and restricts the movement of the motors from the mount by providing a wall for the motor to align.

It is a work in progress because - the motors still move. If you noticed the front part, there is a opening with a hole that is aligned with the front holes of the yellow motor box. We intend to use a metal rod to pass between and hold the front holes of the motors. We might print another piece just to snap between and hold the motors securely.

To use the battery mount piece, you need to print this one first.

This is a 3d printed ball caster mount for the robots described in http://duckietown.org

The original ball caster provided with the dagu chassis is made out of metal and makes noise, so we decided to design this part.

It is for the 3/4" plastic ball caster, Pololu item PL-954. It mounts at the exact place of the original ball caster, it is lighter, and less noisy.

First mount the ball caster with the pololu provided screws. Then pop in the ball. There is an opening in the pololu ball caster part, that has to look to the rear of the robot. Then mount the piece with M3 screws and nuts to the chassis.

Overall if you print the motor mount and the battery holder, you get a slightly better duckiebot that is nicer to operate, and once calibrated it will hold those values for a longer time. The sketch-up file is also included, so you can modify it to your needs.
